Ways we learn restraint without tying it to salvation or creating fake problems:
- Paying attention to what feels good to our bodies re: food, movement, sleep, & touch
- Learning when to talk & when to listen
- Setting boundaries & enforcing them
- healthy emotional expression

I know a lot of these “rules” are just symbolic and ritual. Restraint is an important value to understand, but can be taught without introducing fake problems. Knowing I don’t have to add to my children’s stress by creating problems just to teach them a lesson? CHEF’S KISS 🤌🏼

I find people leave the church when the pain, sorrow, and stress outweigh the joy and fulfillment. Leaving brought me a lot of joy+fulfillment because I no longer stress about things that aren’t real problems. Like drinking tea, showing shoulders, or going to a store on Sunday.

So next time you see a parent complaining or venting about how difficult parenting is…look at them as a person who needs support and not your judgement on how they “chose this.” The United States is sooo bad at supporting parents and we all suffer because of it.

Children aren’t traps & deserve loving parents. Ppl also deserve to know how hard it is to raise kids and not just feel completely off guard when you have them. So from me to you: it’s fucking hard. Especially for women. And society is so cruel to mothers, which makes it harder.

I would have still chosen to have my kids, even if it felt like less of a requirement for life satisfaction..but I wonder if I would have felt a bit more capable in accepting imperfection, asking for help, and feeling less perpetual guilt.

@CecProff I think modeling setting boundaries for your children is another way to help keep them safe & learn to express emotions and their needs. There’s def a line between “you’re crying is making me angry” and “I’m angry because you keep hurting me.” You’re doing great!!!!

@CecProff I don’t think there is anything wrong with saying, “I’m feeling angry because you keep jumping on me when I asked you to stop.” I’ve had to add a boundary at the end of such statements, like “I need to keep myself safe so if you jump on me again, I’m going to sit somewhere else.”

@CecProff Totally!! I agree. I panic a lot because I come from parents who struggled with taking accountability and also dumped their emotions onto others. I think modeling boundaries, accountability, and safe emotional expression goes a long way.

@CecProff I’m also very careful in how I express my emotions. It can be really easy for me to say “that *makes* me mad” or whatever emotion. I’m really deliberate in saying “I feel mad” vs implying anything made me feel a certain way. I encourage my kids to use the same wording.

@CecProff Lately we practice a lot of, “how do you think this person feels when this happens?” w/ my 4 yr old. For instance, how do you think Jack feels when he loses the soccer game? Or how do you think Sophie feels when she opens a present from you? Helps her put herself in others shoes.

You *can* look happier in one picture over another, but it doesn’t possibly capture everything and oftentimes I feel like these “then -vs- now” things that pop up are often a public display of body dysmorphic thinking.

How you look in a picture isn’t a determining factor of how happy you are & honestly, I think it’s one of the biggest blind spots of social media. We control how others see us with pictures/videos, but it’s just another way we strip ourselves of true connection and vulnerability.

Tbh I think so many of us millennials are emotionally struggling because we were born/were children during the peak of the self-esteem boosting era. I think self-compassion is a foreign concept for many of us. I’m not saying it’s the ~solution but I do think it helps.

Self-compassion means being kind to ourselves when life sucks or we notice a flaw, rather than being harshly self-critical. Self-compassion means recognizing that as humans, we are imperfect, which allows us to connect better to others when we suffer.

Self-esteem focuses on feeling valued because of the traits we think we possess (which varies depending on life experiences). Self-compassion focuses on being deserving of compassion + understanding, regardless of the traits we possess.

Just a tidbit I learned that has been helpful for my mental health: focus on self-compassion rather than self-esteem. Accept that there are shitty parts about yourself and give grace rather than trying to eliminate those pieces of you.

I’m not saying DON’T reach out, but I am saying that if the only time you’re caring is when someone is in crisis, it is possible they don’t trust you enough to turn to you.

I’ve honestly only felt sadder when I’ve had people reach out, but only when things are bad. It feels like pity.

I just think the savior mentality isn’t healthy.

This is all coming from someone who has tried to rescue someone (& failed), & someone who has had others try to rescue her. It’s just not as simple as reaching out, but I know that real friendships + regularity help me.

And TREAT PEOPLE NORMALLY. Most of us are not mental health professional. I’ve had plenty of people try to cure me of my problems that it became the basis of the entire relationship. For me, normal relationships help me far more than the occasional “reach out” friend.

Without those things, it is unlikely I would ever reach out to someone in a time of true crisis or that they would recognize one happening with me. So my suggestion is not to just reach out to others, but aim to be a regular and positive part of their life.
And research shows that to truly trust people, you have to actually know them (which entails some level of regularity/predictability). For me, knowing someone requires a level of time+togetherness.

But what I can do is express what helps me amidst my struggles. I can’t speak for others and what they need. For me, regularity/predictability helps. I need someone who is my friend, not just when crisis emerges. I will not reach out to someone I don’t have a level of trust for.

That said, I’ve still lost people to mental health illnesses, even when I’ve poured all my heart and soul into helping them (or helping them get help). It makes me feel helpless in my own way, and makes me unsure what to do.

Here’s the thing, I just don’t know what the right thing is to do or say. I myself have some mental health issues & have reached out to people who have them as well (amidst crisis, or not). I’ve never known if it’s helped, but I can only assume it doesn’t hurt.

But to me, this messed with me more than I realized. Hi, I'm a 24 year old, who is terrified of the dark.
I wish I had talked openly about it sooner, &realized it wasn't my fault. & I know in comparison this doesn't seem all too bad...
MORAL OF THE STORY: if something like this happens, it's not your fault, and don't be afraid to tell people.
I never even reported that this happened because I literally thought that I "asked for it."
It took me a full 2 years before I even told my family, because I was embarrassed that I walked home at night.
I even get scared to walk to the bathroom in the middle of the night, I always feel like there's someone waiting for me.
But here we are, 4 years later, and I still am terrified of the dark - like panic attacks having to walk out to my car at night.
The experience scared me to death, but I did what I always did: I blamed myself for being stupid and walking home, and I laughed it off.
My grandparents were already asleep, but I immediately told some of my friends what had happened. At the time I didn't think much of it.
Eventually, the person caught up to me, groped me, then ran off. I proceeded to start crying on the phone, and ran to my grandparents house.
At this point, I didn't know what to think: is this dude going to rob me, rape me, what?
I was still on the phone, walking progressively faster, and I could hear footsteps behind me progressively getting faster as well.
That's when I realized, passing an apartment complex parking lot 1 block west of 7/11, that the person following me was hiding out there.
At this point, it was pitch black & I was mad and still a bit freaked out, so I called my friend to tell him I was fine despite waking home.
I finally got to the 7/11 on 4th north, at this point the person was now gone - they had turned somewhere so I was relieved.
I got kind of scared at this point, which is typical for me, but I kept talking myself down: "he's just walking home too, don't be scared."
Once I hit about 1000 N, they crossed the street and were now behind me on the same side of the road. It now was pretty dark out.
